 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/uaacheron.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aacheron</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/1/02 8:31:05 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Thoughts of the Wicked</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A Christian would hardly be able to contemplate that God does not exist.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, I am not a Christian, and I keep my mind open to the fact that God <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> might exist</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (in any form at all). Why could Christians not contemplate upon their faith? Would they be conducting blasphemy? What if those contemplations give their faith greater strength? What if it &quot;opens their eyes&quot;, ie. they see the truth of another belief?<br>
<br>
Are Christians so narrow-minded that they cannot accept that they are mere mortals, and can be equally wrong and deceived as I can? If so, I truly pity their souls...<br>
<br>
What separates them from others, so that they need not care about if they're right or wrong, as long as they are Christians? As I see it, they too should <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> think</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Open their minds and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> think</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> about everything, nothing and infinity.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> I am not saying that Christians are wrong, I'm just saying that they <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> can</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be wrong, so they need to keep their minds open to that chance, as do I.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<br>
--Aacheron, &quot;Something Wicked&quot; <p><center><table><tr><td style=filter:glow(color="red",strenght="5")><font color="white">
